This is a list of notable people born in or strongly associated with the [[Isle of Wight]], alphabetically within categories. {{Expand list|date=August 2008}}
==Born on the Isle of Wight== * King [[Arwald]], last pagan king in England and last king of the Isle of Wight, died 686 * Dr [[Thomas Arnold]], headmaster of [[Rugby School]] and immortalised in ''[[Tom Brown's Schooldays]]'', born in [[Cowes]] * [[Danny Briggs]], Hampshire and England cricketer * [[Tom Clarke (Irish republican)|Tom Clarke]], revolutionary leader involved in the 1916 [[Easter Rising]] and executed in [[Dublin]] * [[Sophie Dawes, Baronne de Feuchères]], born in [[St Helens, Isle of Wight|St Helens]] * [[Thomas Fleming (judge)|Thomas Fleming]], judge and Lord Chief Justice * [[Uffa Fox]], yacht designer * [[Vivian Fuchs]], Antarctic explorer * [[Marius Goring]], born [[Newport, Isle of Wight|Newport]] * [[Maxwell Gray]] (Mary Gleed Tuttiett), novelist * [[Sheila Hancock]], actress, born in [[Blackgang]] * [[Robert Hooke]], scientist, born in [[Freshwater]] * [[Jeremy Irons]], actor, born in [[Cowes]] and raised in [[St Helens, Isle of Wight|St Helens]] * [[Craig Sheldon]], writer, born in [[Newport, Isle of Wight|Newport]] * [[Phill Jupitus]], comedian, born in [[Newport, Isle of Wight|Newport]] * [[Mark King (musician)|Mark King]], born in Gurnard nr.Cowes, bass player and vocalist in pop/funk band [[Level 42]] * [[Suri Krishnamma]], film director and writer, born in [[Shanklin]] * Arthur Clifford (Cliff) Michelmore 11 December 1919 Cowes BBC Radio/TV presenter. Also lived in Bembridge in later years. * [[Albert Midlane]], failed ironmonger, poet and hymn writer was born in [[Newport, Isle of Wight|Newport]] * [[Anthony Minghella]], film director; born in [[Ryde]]; his parents run the Minghella's Ice Cream company on the Island; his film ''[[The English Patient (1996 movie)|The English Patient]]'' includes footage of [[Shanklin]] Pier; on accepting his Best Picture [[Academy Awards|Oscar]], he said, "This is a great day for the Isle of Wight!" * [[Loretta Minghella]], charity executive and solicitor * [[Brian Murphy (actor)|Brian Murphy]], actor, born in [[Ventnor]] * [[Noel Odell]], geologist and mountaineer, born in [[St Lawrence, Isle of Wight|St Lawrence]] * Queen [[Osburga]], daughter of Oslac, Chief Butler of England and mother of King [[Alfred the Great]] * [[Arthur Cecil Pigou]], economist and proponent of [[Pigovian tax|pigouvian taxes]], born in [[Ryde]] * [[Albert Pollard]], historian, born in Ryde * [[Horace Rawlins]], golfer, winner of the first [[U.S. Open (golf)|U.S. Open]] in 1895 * [[Henry Sewell]], first [[Prime Minister]] of [[New Zealand]], born on the island in 1807 and lived there until emigrating to New Zealand at the age of 45 * [[Kelly Sotherton]], heptathlete, born in Newport * [[Polly Toynbee]], journalist, born at Yafford<ref>{{cite web|last1=Toynbee|first1=Polly|title=Back on the Isle of Wight, Tory Britain rehearses its collapse|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/apr/07/isle-wight-tory-rehearses-collapse|website=The Guardian|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=7 April 2015|ref=gu}}</ref> * [[Harry Frederick Whitchurch]] V.C., born in Sandown * [[Eric Charles Twelves Wilson]] V.C., born in [[Sandown]] in 1912 * [[Lee Bradbury]], ex professional footballer, currently manager of [[Havant and Waterlooville]], born in [[Cowes]]
==Raised on the Isle of Wight== *[[E. Power Biggs]], [[concert organist]] *[[Uffa Fox]], raised in [[Cowes]] *[[William Hutt (British MP)|William Hutt]], MP and colonial administrator, educated in Ryde *[[George Jellicoe, 2nd Earl Jellicoe|George, 2nd Earl Jellicoe]], at St. Lawrence Hall, [[Ventnor]] *[[Fidelis Morgan]], actress and writer, raised in Bonchurch *Nicholas Dingley alias [[Razzle (musician)|Razzle]], drummer for [[Hanoi Rocks]], raised in [[Binstead]] *[[Algernon Charles Swinburne]], poet, raised in East Dene, [[Bonchurch]] *[[Bear Grylls]], climber, youngest Briton to reach the summit of Mount Everest and live; survival expert; host of Man vs. Wild
==Lived on the Isle of Wight== *[[Sam Browne]], soldier, retired to [[Ryde]] *[[Master Gunner]] [[Daniel Cambridge]] [[Victoria cross|VC]] (later [[Yeoman of the Guard]]), stationed at [[Freshwater Redoubt|Redoubt Battery]], [[Palmerston Forts, Isle of Wight|Fort Redoubt]], [[Freshwater, Isle of Wight|Freshwater Bay]], until 1871 (Census) *[[Julia Margaret Cameron]], photographer, lived in [[Freshwater, Isle of Wight|Freshwater Bay]] *[[Lewis Carroll]], author, lived at [[Sandown]] while working on ''[[Alice in Wonderland]]'' *[[Winston Churchill]], visited [[Ventnor]] for extended periods throughout his life *[[Christopher Cockerell|Sir Christopher Cockerell]], inventor of the hovercraft, spent two years in [[East Cowes]] working on his prototypes *[[Charles Darwin]], naturalist, lived for a period in 1867 in the Kings Head Hotel in [[Sandown]] *[[Charles Dickens]], author, lived in Bonchurch for 3 months in 1849 *[[Charles I of England|King Charles I]], held prisoner in [[Carisbrooke Castle]] for a year *[[Ken Dodd]], comedian, had a holiday home at [[Freshwater, Isle of Wight|Freshwater Bay]] *[[Jack Douglas (actor)|Jack Douglas]], actor from a series of ''Carry On'' films *[[Trevor Duncan]], composer (Dr Finlay's Casebook theme), lived in [[Bonchurch]] *King [[Ethelred the Unready]], fled to the Isle of Wight in 1012 from the Danes under [[Sweyn Forkbeard]] *[[Uffa Fox]], yacht designer, lived in [[Puckaster]] *[[David Gascoyne]], 20th-century surrealist poet *[[Pamela Green]], infamous nude model of the 1950s and 1960s, lived in [[Yarmouth, Isle of Wight|Yarmouth]] with the dambuster [[Douglas Webb]], DFM *King [[Harold Godwinson|Harold II]] and his brother [[Tostig Godwinson]], have estates at Kern and [[Nunwell]] respectively *[[Jet Harris]], musician with The Shadows *[[Peter de Heyno]], defended the [[Carisbrooke Castle]] 1377 against French–Castilian troops *[[Robyn Hitchcock]], musician, lived in [[Yarmouth, Isle of Wight|Yarmouth]] from the mid-1980s to the early 1990s, and cited it in many of his works of the period *[[John Oliver Hobbes]] (Pearl Mary Teresa Craigie), novelist, lived part-time in [[Steephill]], 1900–1906 *[[Geoffrey Hughes]], actor, lived in [[Newport, Isle of Wight|Newport]] *[[John Jellicoe, 1st Earl Jellicoe|Admiral Sir John Jellicoe]], lived at St. Lawrence Hall, [[Ventnor]] *[[John Keats]], poet, moved to the island in 1814; areas of [[Shanklin]] are named after him *[[Charles Kingsley (yacht designer)|Charles Kingsley]], spent childhood there *[[Marek Larwood]], actor and comedian *[[Henry Wadsworth Longfellow]], American poet, spent the summer in [[Shanklin]] in 1868 *[[Guglielmo Marconi]] did radio experiments in [[Alum Bay]] and [[Niton, Isle of Wight|Niton]] around 1900 *[[Karl Marx]], lived in [[Ryde]] in the 1870s and in [[Ventnor]] in the 1880s *[[John Milne]], inventor of the horizontal [[pendulum]] [[seismograph]], retired from the [[Japan]]ese [[Imperial College of Engineering]] in [[Shide, Isle of Wight]] *[[David Niven]], actor, lived in [[Bembridge]] as a child *[[Isaac Pitman]], invented a shorthand system, lived for a time in [[Sandown]] *[[John Morgan Richards]], cigarette and patent medicine entrepreneur, lived in [[Steephill]], 1903–1918 *[[Legh Richmond]], preacher and writer of the religious tract ''[[The Dairyman's Daughter]]'', [[curate]] for [[Yaverland]] and [[Brading]] *[[John Edward Bernard Seely, 1st Baron Mottistone]], [[Secretary of State for War]] during the years leading up to the [[First World War]]; MP and Justice of the Peace for the [[Isle of Wight]] *[[Michael Sheard]], actor, lived in [[Ryde]] *[[Algernon Charles Swinburne]], poet, lived in [[Bonchurch]] * [[Shaw Taylor]], TV presenter, "keep 'em peeled", lived in Totland *[[Alfred Tennyson|Alfred, Lord Tennyson]], poet, lived in [[Farringford]] in [[Freshwater, Isle of Wight|Freshwater Bay]] *[[Margaret Thatcher]], rented a house in [[Seaview, Isle of Wight|Seaview]] *[[Edward Upward]], author, lived in [[Sandown]] from 1961 to 2004, family hailed from the Island *[[Victoria of the United Kingdom|Queen Victoria]], had one of her residences at [[Osborne House]] in [[East Cowes]] *[[Barnes Wallis]], inventor of the bouncing bomb, lived and worked in [[Cowes]] *[[Douglas Webb]], DFM air gunner with 617 Squadron on the Dambusters raid; partner of the infamous nude model [[Pamela Green]]; lived in [[Yarmouth, Isle of Wight|Yarmouth]]
==Still resident== *[[Raymond Allen (scriptwriter)|Raymond Allen]], television scriptwriter best known for ''[[Some Mothers Do 'Ave 'Em]]'', born and lives in [[Ryde]] * [[Patrick Buckland]], CEO of Stainless Games, creator of ''[[Carmageddon]]'' * [[Melvyn Hayes]], actor, lives in Ryde * [[David Icke]], conspiracy theorist, lives in Ryde * [[Mark King (musician)|Mark King]], Level 42 musician * [[Ellen MacArthur|Dame Ellen MacArthur]], sailor, based in Cowes * [[The Osbournes]] have a holiday home in [[Yaverland]] * [[Dick Taylor]], Pretty Things musician * [[Alan Titchmarsh]], author and TV presenter * [[M J Trow]], author and teacher *[[Keegan Brown]], Professional darts player
